      Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow, unless AMC does s=
omething particularly nuts I guess.=C2=A0It will be back on Monday.A! M! C!=
Way back on Tuesday, AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. announced that it had =
sold $230 million of stock to a hedge fund called Mudrick Capital Managemen=
t LP. AMC=E2=80=99s stock went up on continuing wild retail enthusiasm, and=
 Mudrick promptly dumped the stock into the rising market at a profit. This=
 looked like a good trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0I  said yesterday that it was a go=
od trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0though then the stock kept rising and by yesterday =
afternoon it looked less great.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CMudrick Capital may have miss=
ed out on more than $300 million by dumping AMC a day early,=E2=80=9D says =
this CNBC headline. Fine. You win some, you miss out on winning some even m=
ore.=C2=A0One thing that troubled me about the trade was: Why should AMC se=
ll to Mudrick? Why not sell directly to the wildly enthusiastic retail shar=
eholders?=C2=A0I  wrote:=C2=A0=C2=A0The traditional way to do this trade wo=
uld be with an at-the-market offering: Instead of selling the stock to Mudr=
ick to resell to enthusiastic meme-stock traders, AMC could have hired an i=
nvestment bank to sell the stock to enthusiastic meme-stock traders. Then i=
f the stock went up as the bank was selling, AMC would capture the gains ra=
ther than Mudrick. AMC did this back in December, and again in April; I do =
not know why it didn=E2=80=99t do it yesterday.Well the answer is that it=
=E2=80=99s doing it today!On June 3, 2021, AMC Entertainment Holdings, Inc.=
 (the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D) entered into an equity distribution agreem=
ent (the =E2=80=9CEquity Distribution Agreement=E2=80=9D) with B. Riley Sec=
urities, Inc. and Citigroup Global Markets Inc. as sales agents (each, a =
=E2=80=9CSales Agent=E2=80=9D and collectively, the =E2=80=9CSales Agents=
=E2=80=9D), to sell up to 11,550,000 shares of Class A common stock, par va=
lue $0.01 per share, of the Company (the =E2=80=9CCommon Stock=E2=80=9D), f=
rom time to time, through an =E2=80=9Cat-the-market=E2=80=9D offering progr=
am (the =E2=80=9COffering=E2=80=9D).Just continuing terrific stuff from AMC=
. Yesterday it announced that, as a token of appreciation for=C2=A0its reta=
il shareholders, it would give them each=C2=A0a free large popcorn[1]; toda=
y it is selling them more stock. The stock closed yesterday at $62.55. If i=
t sells all 11.5 million shares at that price, it will clear about $722 mil=
lion. That=E2=80=99s a lot of popcorn! Actually=C2=A0it is=C2=A0more than A=
MC spent on=C2=A0food and beverage costs over the last three years. Good de=
al.Of course $62.55 is just some number; this morning, AMC=E2=80=99s stock =
boinged around wildly pre-market and then opened at $58.10 =E2=80=94=C2=A0l=
ower than yesterday=E2=80=99s close though also, to be fair, higher than it=
 had ever traded in its history before yesterday. At 11 a.m., it was tradin=
g at about $45; by the time you read this, it will be some other random num=
ber. AMC could end up selling these shares at $60ish, or at $30ish, or at $=
200ish for all I know. What a fun adventure for them.Here is an amazing par=
agraph from AMC=E2=80=99s risk factors=C2=A0for this offering:From January =
1, 2020 through June 2, 2021, we have issued 449,307,737 shares of our Clas=
s A common stock in a combination of at-the-market sales, conversion of Cla=
ss B common stock, conversion of notes, exchanges of notes, transaction fee=
 payments, and equity grant vesting. As of June 2, 2021, there were 501,780=
,240 shares of Class A common stock issued and outstanding. The dilutive ef=
fect of these issuances was partially offset by the cancellation of 51,769,=
784 shares of our Class B common stock. This offering will increase our out=
standing shares of Class A common stock by up to 11,550,000 additional shar=
es.=C2=A0One year ago today, AMC had 52.5 million shares of Class A stock o=
utstanding (and 104.3 million total shares). After today=E2=80=99s offering=
, it will have 513.3 million shares outstanding. Ninety percent=C2=A0of AMC=
=E2=80=99s Class A stock, and=C2=A0eighty percent=C2=A0of its total stock, =
has been issued over the last 12 months. Some of that was desperation: In l=
ate 2020 and early 2021, with theaters closed due to pandemic and debt pres=
sing on AMC, it diluted its shareholders by selling tens of millions of sha=
res near its all-time-low stock price. Some of it, now, is hilarious joyful=
 opportunism: In June 2021, with an army of retail =E2=80=9C apes=E2=80=9D =
enthusiastically bidding up the stock, it will sell millions of shares at i=
ts all-time high.=C2=A0In the first quarter of 2021, AMC sold a total of ab=
out 187 million shares in at-the-market offerings, for gross proceeds of ab=
out $597 million. That=E2=80=99s an average price of about $3.19 per share.=
 Now it is offering 11.55 million shares, roughly 6%=C2=A0of what it sold i=
n the first quarter, worth $722 million at yesterday=E2=80=99s close. It wi=
ll get more money from this offering, for 6% as much stock.=C2=A0That risk =
factor goes on to discuss AMC=E2=80=99s most pressing corporate finance pro=
blem, which is that it is almost out of authorized shares. As we  discussed=
 yesterday, AMC=E2=80=99s corporate charter allows it to issue up to=C2=A05=
24,173,073 shares of common stock; if it sells all the shares in this offer=
ing, it will have 513,330,240 shares outstanding. That leaves it with about=
 10.8 million shares it could issue in the future, though my math here is n=
ot exact; like most companies, AMC also reserves some shares to issue under=
 its equity-based compensation plan for executives, so the actual number of=
 shares it can sell after today could be quite low indeed.I hope it is 1. I=
 hope that after it completes this offering, AMC announces =E2=80=9Cokay th=
ere is one more AMC share that we can sell, who wants it?=E2=80=9D And then=
 sells it for, like, $69 million. Is The Last AMC Share a non-fungible toke=
n? I mean, not really, in the sense that it is perfectly fungible with ever=
y other AMC share. But if you buy The Last AMC Share you can make sure ever=
yone knows about it, and AMC will probably give you a gold-plated bag of po=
pcorn and a statue of a gorilla to go with your Last Share. It=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0as good as=C2=A0an NFT. It is also much, much funnier than most of the a=
ctual NFT projects. Really I see no reason AMC shouldn=E2=80=99t do this.Oh=
 sure sure sure AMC also keeps talking about amending its charter to author=
ize 500 million more shares, but honestly I think that is the less creative=
 way to deal with the problem. The right way to deal with the problem is to=
 sell very few shares, but sell each of them for a lot of money.Did you kno=
w that I used to be an equity capital markets banker? You probably found it=
 painful=C2=A0to read the last two paragraphs, but think about how I felt w=
riting them. I think back to my banking days and imagine going to a company=
 and saying =E2=80=9Csure you=C2=A0could=C2=A0issue a lot of shares at a cu=
stomary=C2=A0discount to your last closing price, but what if, instead, you=
 sold=C2=A0one=C2=A0share at an astronomical price?=E2=80=9D They would car=
ry me out in a straitjacket. Now I am only partially kidding. Honestly I th=
ink there=E2=80=99s like a 25% chance that AMC really does auction off its =
last share for millions of dollars.Corporate finance! Back in January, when=
 GameStop Corp. was the hot meme stock,  I wrote:One possible conclusion he=
re is that the world in which GameStop is a fun gambling token and up a zil=
lion percent really is cut off from the world in which GameStop is a compan=
y with a CEO and a board and 5,000 struggling stores in malls and a big act=
ivist investor with plans to turn its business around. They can see each ot=
her, but they can never interact. =E2=80=9CHuh, lotta crazy news about some=
thing called =E2=80=98GameStop,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D George Sherman or Ryan Co=
hen might think; =E2=80=9Cit would be weird if they were talking about us.=
=E2=80=9D But they=E2=80=99re not.AMC went in a different direction. AMC wa=
s like =E2=80=9Cyou like gorillas, we will  give you gorillas.=E2=80=9D AMC=
 looks at the price signal sent by the stock market and takes it=C2=A0absol=
utely seriously. AMC sees its stock price rise and says, well, the market b=
elieves that we are an extraordinarily successful company that has many hig=
h-value projects available to us, so we must take all of the market=E2=80=
=99s money and invest it in those projects.=C2=A0You=C2=A0might look at the=
 stock-price rally and say =E2=80=9Cthis is about Reddit and memes, not the=
 present value of AMC=E2=80=99s future cash flows,=E2=80=9D but=C2=A0AMC=C2=
=A0will never say that.[2] AMC is just like =E2=80=9Cthe market places an e=
normous value on our future cash flows so let=E2=80=99s=C2=A0go find some.=
=E2=80=9DThough, here=E2=80=99s another excerpt from the risk factors:We be=
lieve that the recent volatility and our current market prices reflect mark=
et and trading dynamics unrelated to our underlying business, or macro or i=
ndustry fundamentals, and we do not know how long these dynamics will last.=
 Under the circumstances, we caution you against investing in our Class A c=
ommon stock, unless you are prepared to incur the risk of losing all or a s=
ubstantial portion of your investment.Extreme fluctuations in the market pr=
ice of our Class A common stock have been accompanied by reports of strong =
and atypical retail investor interest, including on social media and online=
 forums. The market volatility and trading patterns we have experienced cre=
ate several risks for investors, including the following: =E2=80=A6factors =
in the public trading market for our Class A common stock include the senti=
ment of retail investors (including as may be expressed on financial tradin=
g and other social media sites and online forums), the direct access by ret=
ail investors to broadly available trading platforms, the amount and status=
 of short interest in our securities, access to margin debt, trading in opt=
ions and other derivatives on our Class A common stock and any related hedg=
ing and other trading factors.Here AMC is, warning investors that its stock=
 has gone crazy because of retail investors on Reddit (=E2=80=9Cincluding o=
n social media and online forums=E2=80=9D) and Robinhood (=E2=80=9Cbroadly =
available trading platforms=E2=80=9D), because of  gamma squeezes (=E2=80=
=9Ctrading in options =E2=80=A6=C2=A0and any related hedging=E2=80=9D) and =
short squeezes (=E2=80=9Camount and status of short interest=E2=80=9D), and=
 for no good fundamental reason (=E2=80=9Cdynamics unrelated to our underly=
ing business=E2=80=9D). In sum, AMC says,=C2=A0do not buy the stock we are =
selling you=C2=A0(=E2=80=9Cwe caution you against investing in our Class A =
common stock=E2=80=9D).It=E2=80=99s selling it anyway, of course. Why not! =
Last spring, Hertz Global Holdings Inc., =E2=80=9Cthe original meme stock,=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0was also the subject of wild retail-investor enthusiasm desp=
ite being actually in bankruptcy. Hertz looked around and  thought =E2=80=
=9Chey let=E2=80=99s sell these people some stock=E2=80=9D; it  put out a p=
rospectus telling people not to buy the stock, and then started selling the=
m the stock. The Securities and Exchange Commission quickly shut this down;=
 it did not exactly explain why but, you know, sure, it=E2=80=99s not exact=
ly a great look to tell retail investors not to buy your stock and sell it =
to them anyway. Before the SEC stepped in, Hertz managed to  sell $29 milli=
on worth of stock at an average price of about $2.08 per share. Since then =
Hertz  got much better, its plan to emerge from bankruptcy involves a signi=
ficant recovery for shareholders, and the stock closed yesterday at $6.38. =
If you bought Hertz stock from Hertz when Hertz told you not to =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0before the SEC stepped in to prevent you from doing that =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0you did great.=C2=A0If you buy AMC stock from AMC when AMC tells you not=
 to, will you also do great? I mean, I would bet against it, but I wouldn=
=E2=80=99t bet very much. =E2=80=9CWhat is anything worth,=E2=80=9D DealBoo=
k asked today. Anything! Is! Worth! What! People! Will! Pay! For! It! I hav=
e no idea, man. The important thing is that the stock comes with popcorn.Bi=
tConnectBitConnect was a cryptocurrency project and also maybe a Ponzi sche=
me that collapsed in January 2018, taking most of its investors=E2=80=99 mo=
ney with it. Without getting into the details =E2=80=94=C2=A0which involved=
 multilevel marketing, BitConnect=E2=80=99s own cryptocurrency, etc. =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the basic idea was that you could deposit your Bitcoins with BitCo=
nnect and earn =E2=80=9Cinterest=E2=80=9D on your =E2=80=9Cloans=E2=80=9D t=
hanks to the efforts of BitConnect=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CTrading Bot.=E2=80=9D=
 Loosely speaking, you would deposit your cryptocurrency into a pool that w=
ould support automated trading in speculative cryptocurrency markets, and i=
n exchange you=E2=80=99d get daily interest on your deposit based on the su=
ccess of the automated market-making program.Last week the U.S. Securities =
and Exchange Commission sued five alleged BitConnect promoters. The SEC=E2=
=80=99s complaint does not use the word =E2=80=9CPonzi=E2=80=9D once. Inste=
ad, here is the bad thing that the promoters allegedly did:From approximate=
ly January 2017 to January 2018, BitConnect, an unincorporated organization=
, raised approximately $2 billion by conducting an unregistered offering an=
d sale of securities in the form of investments into BitConnect=E2=80=99s =
=E2=80=9Clending program.=E2=80=9D Defendants Brown, Grant, Maasen, and Nob=
le, along with BitConnect itself and others, offered and sold the lending p=
rogram as securities without registering the offering with the SEC as requi=
red by the federal securities laws and without a valid exemption from this =
registration requirement. Defendant Jeppesen aided and abetted BitConnect=
=E2=80=99s unregistered offer and sale of these securities.To raise over $2=
 billion from these unregistered offers and sales of securities, BitConnect=
 used a network of promoters=E2=80=94including Brown, Grant, Maasen, and No=
ble=E2=80=94who advertised the merits of investing in BitConnect=E2=80=99s =
lending program to prospective retail investors and in return received a pe=
rcentage of the invested funds they obtained. They did so without being reg=
istered as broker-dealers with the SEC, as the federal securities laws requ=
ire.To conduct its offer and sale of securities, BitConnect told investors =
it would deploy investor funds to trade in and profit from the volatility o=
f Bitcoin. In return, BitConnect promised to pay investors the resulting pr=
ofits, which BitConnect promised could be as high as approximately 40% per =
month. ...The definition of a =E2=80=9Csecurity=E2=80=9D under the Securiti=
es Act includes a wide range of investment vehicles, including =E2=80=9Cinv=
estment contracts.=E2=80=9D As the United States Supreme Court noted in SEC=
 v. W.J. Howey Co., Congress defined =E2=80=9Csecurity=E2=80=9D broadly to =
embody a =E2=80=9Cflexible rather than a static principle, one that is capa=
ble of adaptation to meet the countless and variable schemes devised by=C2=
=A0those who seek the use of the money of others on the promise of profits,=
=E2=80=9D 328 U.S. 293, 299 (1946), such that =E2=80=9Cinvestment contracts=
=E2=80=9D are instruments, schemes, or transactions through which a person =
invests money in a common enterprise and reasonably expects profits or retu=
rns derived from the entrepreneurial or managerial efforts of others. Court=
s have found that novel or unique investment vehicles constitute investment=
 contracts, including interests in orange groves, animal breeding programs,=
 railroads, mobile phones, and enterprises that exist only on the Internet.=
 ...As the foregoing demonstrates, BitConnect marketed and promoted the Len=
ding=C2=A0Program as essentially guaranteeing investors profits based solel=
y upon BitConnect=E2=80=99s (and its supposed Trading Bot=E2=80=99s) entrep=
reneurial and managerial efforts.In fact, because BitConnect marketed the T=
rading Bot that formed the supposed centerpiece of the Lending Program as p=
roprietary, investors had no control over the success or failure of their L=
ending Program investment and could take no steps that would determine the =
fate of their investments=E2=80=94all investors could do was decide whether=
, when, and how much to invest into the Lending Program, and whether to wit=
hdraw supposed returns after the lock-up periods required them to do so.=C2=
=A0There are some insinuations of Ponzi there (=E2=80=9Csupposed returns,=
=E2=80=9D etc.), but that=E2=80=99s not the intellectual heart of the case.=
 The heart of it is that=C2=A0Bitcoin=C2=A0is not a security, but the poole=
d lending program that BitConnect advertised =E2=80=94=C2=A0in which people=
 lend their Bitcoins to support automated trading of Bitcoin =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0is a security. (Whether or not BitConnect actually did=C2=A0what it adve=
rtised.) Which seems quite right! Oranges are not securities, but when peop=
le pool their money to invest in an orange-grove business, that is a securi=
ty.In other news here=E2=80=99s a Wall Street Journal article about DeFi:Sh=
ort for decentralized finance, DeFi is an umbrella term for financial servi=
ces offered on public blockchains. Like traditional banks, DeFi application=
s allow users to borrow, lend, earn interest, and trade assets and derivati=
ves, among other things. The collection of services is often used by people=
 seeking to borrow against their crypto holdings to place even larger bets.=
 =E2=80=A6Assets deposited as collateral on DeFi platforms, a measure known=
 as total locked value, have grown to more than $100 billion, of which abou=
t $64 billion is on Ethereum, according to the website DeFi Pulse. A year a=
go, there were only about $1 billion of DeFi assets on Ethereum. ...For use=
rs, the appeal of DeFi is simple. There are almost no requirements to parti=
cipate, except for having some form of crypto as collateral. Interest rates=
 are attractive compared with traditional investment products. And because =
transactions are automated, settlement is virtually instantaneous, removing=
 some of the traditional counterparty risk.One important part of DeFi is =
=E2=80=9Cyield farming,=E2=80=9D explained on this  Bloomberg Odd Lots podc=
ast. Basically there=E2=80=99s some=C2=A0smart contract that functions as a=
n automated market maker between two cryptocurrency coins. In order to serv=
e as a market maker, the smart contract needs an inventory of both coins, w=
hich it gets from people =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cyield farmers=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0who agree to deposit some of both coins into the smart contract=
. And then the smart contract makes markets between the two coins, and hope=
fully makes a profit, and pays that profit out to the depositors in the for=
m of interest.=C2=A0This is different from BitConnect! You can go read the =
smart contracts=E2=80=99 code, for one thing, so it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0unlikely=
 that most of them are Ponzis. They are decentralized: You are not relying =
on the unobservable efforts of some entrepreneur (or the entrepreneur=E2=80=
=99s bot), but on open-source code that runs on a decentralized blockchain.=
 Still there are some obvious similarities: You deposit your not-a-security=
 cryptocurrencies into a pool that supports automated trading, and you get =
back interest. When BitConnect offered that product, the SEC decided it was=
 an unregistered security and (belatedly) shut it down. What should the SEC=
 think about DeFi?


