The deliIt=E2=80=99s been a while, but=C2=A0Jesse Barron at the New York Ti=
mes Magazine has gotten a lot closer to resolving=C2=A0the mystery of Your =
Hometown Deli, the deli that is also a $100 million or maybe $2 billion pub=
lic company. When we  last talked about the deli in April, I said it was a =
=E2=80=9Cweird SPAC,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ca shell company that will be used to=
 take an Asian company public in the U.S.=E2=80=9D That still seems correct=
, and Barron fills in more details about the plan.Still mysteries remain. F=
or instance, why did Hometown International Inc. start making public filing=
s in the first place, years before it started attracting high-powered Asian=
 financiers as investors? Also, if it=E2=80=99s a reverse-merger shell, the=
 deli should not be worth $100 million, so why has its stock gone up so muc=
h? Barron writes:I asked Jain the question that drew me to the story to beg=
in with. If the stock price didn=E2=80=99t matter for the merger ratio, why=
 had the shareholders bothered trading it upward? =E2=80=9CMaso Capital has=
 no knowledge on the buying or selling in HWIN,=E2=80=9D Jain said. He adde=
d that Maso had not traded any shares since the initial investment.A former=
 S.E.C. staff member suggested that HWIN's valuation could be part of a lon=
g-term plan to =E2=80=9Cuplist,=E2=80=9D or move the stock from the O.T.C. =
markets to an exchange like the Nasdaq =E2=80=94 market capitalization bein=
g one criterion the exchanges may use when agreeing to list a company. Exch=
anges offer more prestige than the O.T.C., a brighter halo of prestige, and=
 their higher volume of transactions makes it easier to move shares without=
 disturbing the underlying price, a benefit for anyone trying to execute a =
bunch of warrants (for example). But it seemed very unlikely that the marke=
t capitalization of the new entity would resemble the market cap of HWIN =
=E2=80=94 and anyway, there were tons of other barriers to uplisting that H=
ometown might not clear.I am increasingly comfortable with the possibility =
that we will never actually understand what was going on at the deli. I don=
=E2=80=99t understand what=E2=80=99s going on at AMC! Why should stock pric=
es make sense?SPAC kingI enjoyed this New Yorker profile of serial SPAC spo=
nsor Chamath Palihapitiya,=C2=A0a billionaire venture capitalist who noneth=
eless says mean things about billionaires and venture capitalists. One impo=
rtant theme of the profile, I think, is that the essential skill in finance=
 is not really predicting the future or evaluating business plans but=C2=A0=
salesmanship, and that if you are an enormously talented salesperson you wi=
ll go far.Another important theme is that sales is a deeply humanistic and =
all-encompassing endeavor: Great salespeople=C2=A0are not in the business o=
f pushing products but of making people love them as people; once you can d=
o that, selling products is easy. The article makes it clear that=C2=A0Pali=
hapitiya is a great salesperson.=C2=A0So for instance he was an early Faceb=
ook Inc. employee:The C.E.O., Mark Zuckerberg, asked him to oversee efforts=
 to grow the social network=E2=80=99s audience. Given that Facebook was exp=
anding with little effort, this task, as one of Palihapitiya=E2=80=99s form=
er colleagues put it to me, =E2=80=9Cwasn=E2=80=99t sexy,=E2=80=9D and few =
colleagues wanted to join his team. To recruit co-workers, Palihapitiya pro=
mised them the most important project of their lives. Facebook would perish=
 if it didn=E2=80=99t defeat MySpace and other social-media rivals. His tea=
m members would be underdogs fighting for a brighter future. To emphasize h=
is point, Palihapitiya sometimes recalled a time he=E2=80=99d won fifty tho=
usand dollars playing poker and then had gone to a BMW dealership. The sale=
sman=E2=80=94eying Palihapitiya=E2=80=99s rumpled clothes and brown skin=E2=
=80=94refused him a test drive. Palihapitiya walked across the street to Me=
rcedes-Benz, bought a car, and then drove it into the BMW parking lot to ta=
unt the guy who=E2=80=99d rebuffed him. Palihapitiya assured Facebook colle=
agues that, if they joined him, they were showing up every bully=E2=80=94la=
nding a blow for people who looked different and had unfamiliar pedigrees. =
Soon, many top employees were clamoring to join Palihapitiya=E2=80=99s grou=
p. One told me, =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s intoxicating to hear someone describe=
 your work like it=E2=80=99s this noble calling.=E2=80=9D Within four years=
, Facebook was closing in on a billion users. Today, four of Facebook=E2=80=
=99s top executives are alumni of Palihapitiya=E2=80=99s team.In hindsight,=
 it seems unlikely that=C2=A0growing Facebook=E2=80=99s audience was the mo=
st important project of their lives, or that it created a brighter future, =
or that it struck a blow against bullying. But that=E2=80=99s not the point=
, and there=E2=80=99s not even a real argument for those claims. Instead th=
e argument was Palihapitiya=E2=80=99s=C2=A0personal=C2=A0appeal, a story ab=
out himself that somehow became a vague metaphor for his Facebook team.But =
a third theme is that, to be a truly great salesperson, you don=E2=80=99t n=
eed everyone to love you, you just need the=C2=A0right=C2=A0people to love =
you, and sometimes the way to do that is to have the wrong people hate you:=
Other Palihapitiya stories go viral because they capture how delectably out=
rageous he can be. In 2019, when he was trying to persuade investors to sup=
port his first SPAC=E2=80=94for the space-tourism company Virgin Galactic=
=E2=80=94he met in New York with a group of mutual-fund managers and gave a=
 dazzling speech about helping mankind reach for the heavens. =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0One listener=E2=80=94an older gentleman, conservatively dressed=E2=80=94=
began interrupting Palihapitiya to question both his track record and his p=
rojections. Palihapitiya let the man spout off for a bit, and then replied,=
 =E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99re a complete ... idiot.=E2=80=9DThe older man looked=
 as if someone had just punched him.=E2=80=9CHave you even looked at the pr=
ospectus? Did you even ... Google me before you came in here?=E2=80=9DAll t=
he eyes in the room went wide. =E2=80=9CHow lazy are you?=E2=80=9D Palihapi=
tiya said. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t even want your ... money.=E2=80=9DSilen=
ce. Then one of the younger listeners started chuckling. Everyone under the=
 age of fifty began grinning uncontrollably: now they had a Palihapitiya st=
ory of their own. =E2=80=9CIt was brilliant,=E2=80=9D an attendee told me. =
=E2=80=9CIt was completely calculated. That old guy wasn=E2=80=99t ever gon=
na invest in space tourism. But the other people in the room=E2=80=94they l=
oved it!=E2=80=9DAbout half of the investors called Palihapitiya=E2=80=99s =
office afterward to say that they wanted in on the deal. =E2=80=9CPeople ei=
ther love Chamath or they hate him, and that=E2=80=99s fantastic, because p=
olarization gets attention,=E2=80=9D the attendee said. =E2=80=9CPolarizati=
on gets you on CNBC, it gets you Twitter followers, it gets you a megaphone=
. If you believe that Chamath can get an hour on CNBC to explain Virgin Gal=
actic, then you want to buy into this deal, because attention is money.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0I have bleeped some swears there; one way to be polarizing is b=
y swearing a lot. =E2=80=9CEverybody wants in on this deal=E2=80=9D is a go=
od way to sell a deal, but =E2=80=9Call the young cool forward-thinking peo=
ple want in on this deal and all the stuck-in-the-past losers don't=E2=80=
=9D is somehow even better. In investing =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly in tec=
h investing =E2=80=94=C2=A0 the main goal is to be contrarian; if everyone =
loves you then you are not contrarian enough. You have to cultivate the rig=
ht friends and also the right enemies.Things happenElon Musk Files Trademar=
k Paperwork for  Tesla Restaurant Concept. SEC Is Running Out of Options to=
 Rein In Elon Musk. =E2=80=98Game over=E2=80=99: Investors hunt for new mod=
el after years of broad gains.=C2=A0Dogecoin Price Jumps on Coinbase Debut =
Prospect. Defiant  Meme-Stock Short Sellers Stare Down $4.5 Billion Loss. T=
rafigura warned Credit Suisse over Gupta invoice last year. =E2=80=9CThere =
are many infuriating things about the world, but one of the more fixable is=
 the sensation of acute regret from having ordered wrong. Why are there pos=
sibly wrong orders?=E2=80=9D=C2=A03-year-old piano prodigy set to perform a=
t Carnegie Hall.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy em=
ail form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscribe at this link. Or you c=
an subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Tha=
nks![1] Here is a tweet that made me laugh: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m excited fo=
r all the short sellers that will have to cover the Large Popcorn dividend.=
=E2=80=9D See, when you are short a stock, if the stock pays a dividend, yo=
u have to deliver the dividend to your stock lender. Normally dividends are=
 in the form of cash, so you pay cash to the lender. (Or they are in the fo=
rm of stock, so you owe the lender more stock.) But in theory dividends can=
 come in weird forms, and then you have to go out and source the weird thin=
g to deliver to the lender. Overstock.com Inc. infamously tried to pay a di=
vidend in the form of its own non-tradable crypto-stock, in order to mess w=
ith short sellers who would be unable to buy it; ultimately it abandoned th=
e idea but it was a clever form of vengeance on short sellers. A popcorn di=
vidend is less devastating =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s easy enough to buy a=
 large popcorn at an AMC theater =E2=80=94=C2=A0and anyway AMC=E2=80=99s =
=E2=80=9CInvestor Connect=E2=80=9D shareholder-appreciation program is not =
technically a dividend and does not create any obligations for short seller=
s. Still, good joke.[2] Except in its prospectus, lol.
