<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, unless AMC does something particularly nuts I gu=
ess.=C2=A0It will be back on Monday.</em></p><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold=
; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; lette=
r-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-s=
tyle: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">A! =
M! C!</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Way back on Tuesday, AMC Entertainme=
nt Holdings Inc. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
4043760.266861/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1=
NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMDc0NTg0L3RtMjExNzk4NmQzX2RlZmExNGEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBae4cd97d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">announced</a> that it had sold $230 million of stock to a hedg=
e fund called Mudrick Capital Management LP. AMC=E2=80=99s stock went up on=
 continuing wild retail enthusiasm, and Mudrick promptly dumped the stock i=
nto the rising market at a profit. This looked like a good trade =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.2=
66861/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtM=
DIvYW1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdXQtdGhlLXBvcGNvcm4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdd562277" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> said yeste=
rday</a> that it was a good trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0though then the stock kept=
 rising and by yesterday afternoon it looked less great.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CMudr=
ick Capital may have missed out on more than $300 million by dumping AMC a =
day early,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/24043760.266861/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAyMS8wNi8wMi9tdWRyaWNrLWNhc=
Gl0YWwtbWF5LWhhdmUtbWlzc2VkLW91dC1vbi1tb3JlLXRoYW4tMzAwLW1pbGxpb24tYnktZHVt=
cGluZy1hbWMtYS1kYXktZWFybHkuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb1739979" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">says this CNBC =
headline</a>. Fine. You win some, you miss out on winning some even more.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that troubled me about the=
 trade was: Why should AMC sell to Mudrick? Why not sell directly to the wi=
ldly enthusiastic retail shareholders?=C2=A0I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.266861/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDIvYW1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdXQtdGhlLXBvcGNvcm=
4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCdd562277" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote</a>:=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The traditional way to do this trade would be with an =
at-the-market offering: Instead of selling the stock to Mudrick to resell t=
o enthusiastic meme-stock traders, AMC could have hired an investment bank =
to sell the stock to enthusiastic meme-stock traders. Then if the stock wen=
t up as the bank was selling, AMC would capture the gains rather than Mudri=
ck. AMC did this back in December, and again in April; I do not know why it=
 didn=E2=80=99t do it yesterday.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Well the answer is that it=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/24043760.266861/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L=
0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTQxMTU3OS8wMDAxMTA0NjU5MjEwNzYwOTEvdG0yMTE4Mzcz=
ZDJfOGsuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB90fe4793" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">doing it today</a>!</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On June 3, 2021, AMC Entertainment Holdings, Inc=
. (the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D) entered into an equity distribution agree=
ment (the =E2=80=9CEquity Distribution Agreement=E2=80=9D) with B. Riley Se=
curities, Inc. and Citigroup Global Markets Inc. as sales agents (each, a =
=E2=80=9CSales Agent=E2=80=9D and collectively, the =E2=80=9CSales Agents=
=E2=80=9D), to sell up to 11,550,000 shares of Class A common stock, par va=
lue $0.01 per share, of the Company (the =E2=80=9CCommon Stock=E2=80=9D), f=
rom time to time, through an =E2=80=9Cat-the-market=E2=80=9D offering progr=
am (the =E2=80=9COffering=E2=80=9D).</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Just continuing terrific stuff from AMC. Yesterday it <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.266861/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
c2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMDc1Mzk1L3R=
tMjExNzg5N2QzX2RlZmExNGEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB01e1de9a" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">announced</a> that=
, as a token of appreciation for=C2=A0its retail shareholders, it would giv=
e them each=C2=A0a free large popcorn[1]; today it is selling them more sto=
ck. The stock closed yesterday at $62.55. If it sells all 11.5 million shar=
es at that price, it will clear about $722 million. That=E2=80=99s a lot of=
 popcorn! Actually=C2=A0it is=C2=A0more than AMC spent on=C2=A0<a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.266861/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTQxMTU3OS8wMDAxNDExNTc5M=
jEwMDAwMDYvYW1jLTIwMjAxMjMxeDEway5odG0jSXRlbThGaW5hbmNpYWxTdGF0ZW1lbnRzYW5k=
U3VwcGxlbWVudGFyeQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB251512d4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" title=3D"see page 83" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">food and =
beverage costs</a> over the last three years. Good deal.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Of course $62.55 is just some number; this morning, AMC=E2=80=
=99s stock boinged around wildly pre-market and then opened at $58.10 =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0lower than yesterday=E2=80=99s close though also, to be fair, h=
igher than it had ever traded in its history before yesterday. At 11 a.m., =
it was trading at about $45; by the time you read this, it will be some oth=
er random number. AMC could end up selling these shares at $60ish, or at $3=
0ish, or at $200ish for all I know. What a fun adventure for them.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is an amazing paragraph from <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.266861/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2V=
jLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMDc2MDkwL3RtMj=
ExODM3My0xXzQyNGI1Lmh0bSN0UklGQQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB98803a8b" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">AMC=E2=80=99s ris=
k factors</a>=C2=A0for this offering:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">From January 1, 2020 through June 2, 2021, we have issued 449,307,73=
7 shares of our Class A common stock in a combination of at-the-market sale=
s, conversion of Class B common stock, conversion of notes, exchanges of no=
tes, transaction fee payments, and equity grant vesting. As of June 2, 2021=
, there were 501,780,240 shares of Class A common stock issued and outstand=
ing. The dilutive effect of these issuances was partially offset by the can=
cellation of 51,769,784 shares of our Class B common stock. This offering w=
ill increase our outstanding shares of Class A common stock by up to 11,550=
,000 additional shares.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.266861/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTQxMTU3OS8wM=
DAxNDExNTc5MjAwMDAwNTgvYW1jLTIwMjAwMzMxeDEwcS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Cf623654d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>One year ago today</a>, AMC had 52.5 million shares of Class A stock outst=
anding (and 104.3 million total shares). After today=E2=80=99s offering, it=
 will have 513.3 million shares outstanding. <em>Ninety percent=C2=A0</em>o=
f AMC=E2=80=99s Class A stock, and=C2=A0<em>eighty percent=C2=A0</em>of its=
 total stock, has been issued over the last 12 months. Some of that was des=
peration: In late 2020 and early 2021, with theaters closed due to pandemic=
 and debt pressing on AMC, it diluted its shareholders by selling tens of m=
illions of shares near its all-time-low stock price. Some of it, now, is hi=
larious joyful opportunism: In June 2021, with an army of retail =E2=80=9C<=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.266861/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDEvaG93LW=
FtYy1zLWJvc3Mtd29uLW92ZXItdGhlLXJlZGRpdC1jcm93ZA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7=
b86caa6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> =
apes</a>=E2=80=9D enthusiastically bidding up the stock, it will sell milli=
ons of shares at its all-time high.=C2=A0In the first quarter of 2021, AMC =
sold a total of about 187 million shares in at-the-market offerings, for <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.266861/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTQxMTU3OS8wMDA=
xNDExNTc5MjEwMDAwMzgvYW1jLTIwMjEwMzMxeDEwcS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cD8=
621a8ec" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" title=3D"see page 2=
2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">gross proceeds of about $597 million</a>. That=E2=80=
=99s an average price of about $3.19 per share. Now it is offering 11.55 mi=
llion shares, roughly <em>6%=C2=A0</em>of what it sold in the first quarter=
, worth $722 million at yesterday=E2=80=99s close. It will get more money f=
rom this offering, for 6% as much stock.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">That risk factor goes on to discuss AMC=E2=80=99s most pressing corpora=
te finance problem, which is that it is almost out of authorized shares. As=
 we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.26686=
1/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDIvY=
W1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdXQtdGhlLXBvcGNvcm4/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cDdd562277" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> discussed yest=
erday</a>, AMC=E2=80=99s corporate charter allows it to issue up to=C2=A052=
4,173,073 shares of common stock; if it sells all the shares in this offeri=
ng, it will have 513,330,240 shares outstanding. That leaves it with about =
10.8 million shares it could issue in the future, though my math here is no=
t exact; like most companies, AMC also reserves some shares to issue under =
its <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.26686=
1/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTA0N=
zQ2OTIxMDAwNjUwL2EyMjQzMDIyemRlZjE0YS5odG0jZHM0NzgwMV9wcm9wb3NlZF9hbWVuZG1l=
bnQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc9862662" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: sol=
id; background-color: #ccc;">equity-based compensation plan</a> for executi=
ves, so the actual number of shares it can sell after today could be quite =
low indeed.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I hope it is 1. I hope that aft=
er it completes this offering, AMC announces =E2=80=9Cokay there is one mor=
e AMC share that we can sell, who wants it?=E2=80=9D And then sells it for,=
 like, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.26=
6861/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhldmVyZ2UuY29tLzIwMjEvMy8xMS8yMjMyNTA1NC9iZWVwbGUtY2=
hyaXN0aWVzLW5mdC1zYWxlLWNvc3QtZXZlcnlkYXlzLTY5LW1pbGxpb24/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB90f775a7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">$69 million</a>. Is The Last AMC Share a non-fungible token? I mean=
, not really, in the sense that it is perfectly fungible with every other A=
MC share. But if you buy The Last AMC Share you can make sure everyone know=
s about it, and AMC will probably give you a gold-plated bag of popcorn and=
 a statue of a gorilla to go with your Last Share. It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>as=
 good as=C2=A0</em>an NFT. It is also much, much funnier than most of the a=
ctual NFT projects. Really I see no reason AMC shouldn=E2=80=99t do this.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh sure sure sure AMC also keeps talking abo=
ut amending its charter to authorize 500 million more shares, but honestly =
I think that is the less creative way to deal with the problem. The right w=
ay to deal with the problem is to sell very few shares, but sell each of th=
em for a lot of money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Did you know that I =
used to be an equity capital markets banker? You probably found it painful=
=C2=A0to read the last two paragraphs, but think about how I felt writing t=
hem. I think back to my banking days and imagine going to a company and say=
ing =E2=80=9Csure you=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>issue a lot of shares at a c=
ustomary=C2=A0discount to your last closing price, but what if, instead, yo=
u sold=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>share at an astronomical price?=E2=80=9D They=
 would carry me out in a straitjacket. Now I am only partially kidding. Hon=
estly I think there=E2=80=99s like a 25% chance that AMC really does auctio=
n off its last share for millions of dollars.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Corporate finance! Back in January, when GameStop Corp. was the hot meme=
 stock, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24043760.2=
66861/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtM=
jcvcmVkZGl0LWRyaXZlbi1zdXJnZS1wdXRzLWdhbWVzdG9wLWFuZC1yeWFuLWNvaGVuLWluLWEt=
d2VpcmQtc3BvdA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7b22d93b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
