border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">this New Yorker profil=
e</a> of serial SPAC sponsor Chamath Palihapitiya,=C2=A0a billionaire ventu=
re capitalist who nonetheless says mean things about billionaires and ventu=
re capitalists. One important theme of the profile, I think, is that the es=
sential skill in finance is not really predicting the future or evaluating =
business plans but=C2=A0<em>salesmanship</em>, and that if you are an enorm=
ously talented salesperson you will go far.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Another important theme is that sales is a deeply humanistic and all-encom=
passing endeavor: Great salespeople=C2=A0are not in the business of pushing=
 products but of making people love them as people; once you can do that, s=
elling products is easy. The article makes it clear that=C2=A0Palihapitiya =
is a great salesperson.=C2=A0So for instance he was an early Facebook Inc. =
employee:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The C.E.O., Mark Zuck=
erberg, asked him to oversee efforts to grow the social network=E2=80=99s a=
udience. Given that Facebook was expanding with little effort, this task, a=
s one of Palihapitiya=E2=80=99s former colleagues put it to me, =E2=80=9Cwa=
sn=E2=80=99t sexy,=E2=80=9D and few colleagues wanted to join his team. To =
recruit co-workers, Palihapitiya promised them the most important project o=
f their lives. Facebook would perish if it didn=E2=80=99t defeat MySpace an=
d other social-media rivals. His team members would be underdogs fighting f=
or a brighter future. To emphasize his point, Palihapitiya sometimes recall=
ed a time he=E2=80=99d won fifty thousand dollars playing poker and then ha=
d gone to a BMW dealership. The salesman=E2=80=94eying Palihapitiya=E2=80=
=99s rumpled clothes and brown skin=E2=80=94refused him a test drive. Palih=
apitiya walked across the street to Mercedes-Benz, bought a car, and then d=
rove it into the BMW parking lot to taunt the guy who=E2=80=99d rebuffed hi=
m. Palihapitiya assured Facebook colleagues that, if they joined him, they =
were showing up every bully=E2=80=94landing a blow for people who looked di=
fferent and had unfamiliar pedigrees. Soon, many top employees were clamori=
ng to join Palihapitiya=E2=80=99s group. One told me, =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s=
 intoxicating to hear someone describe your work like it=E2=80=99s this nob=
le calling.=E2=80=9D Within four years, Facebook was closing in on a billio=
n users. Today, four of Facebook=E2=80=99s top executives are alumni of Pal=
ihapitiya=E2=80=99s team.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In h=
indsight, it seems unlikely that=C2=A0growing Facebook=E2=80=99s audience w=
as the most important project of their lives, or that it created a brighter=
 future, or that it struck a blow against bullying. But that=E2=80=99s not =
the point, and there=E2=80=99s not even a real argument for those claims. I=
nstead the argument was Palihapitiya=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>personal=C2=A0</em>=
appeal, a story about himself that somehow became a vague metaphor for his =
Facebook team.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But a third theme is that, t=
o be a truly great salesperson, you don=E2=80=99t need everyone to love you=
, you just need the=C2=A0<em>right=C2=A0</em>people to love you, and someti=
mes the way to do that is to have the wrong people hate you:</p><blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Other Palihapitiya stories go viral because t=
hey capture how delectably outrageous he can be. In 2019, when he was tryin=
g to persuade investors to support his first SPAC=E2=80=94for the space-tou=
rism company Virgin Galactic=E2=80=94he met in New York with a group of mut=
ual-fund managers and gave a dazzling speech about helping mankind reach fo=
r the heavens. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One listener=
=E2=80=94an older gentleman, conservatively dressed=E2=80=94began interrupt=
ing Palihapitiya to question both his track record and his projections. Pal=
ihapitiya let the man spout off for a bit, and then replied, =E2=80=9CYou=
=E2=80=99re a complete ... idiot.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
The older man looked as if someone had just punched him.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CHave you even looked at the prospectus? Did you even=
 ... Google me before you came in here?=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">All the eyes in the room went wide. =E2=80=9CHow lazy are you?=E2=80=
=9D Palihapitiya said. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t even <em>want</em> your ...=
 money.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Silence. Then one of the y=
ounger listeners started chuckling. Everyone under the age of fifty began g=
rinning uncontrollably: now they had a Palihapitiya story of their own. =E2=
=80=9CIt was brilliant,=E2=80=9D an attendee told me. =E2=80=9CIt was compl=
etely calculated. That old guy wasn=E2=80=99t <em>ever</em> gonna invest in=
 space tourism. But the other people in the room=E2=80=94they loved it!=E2=
=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">About half of the investors called P=
alihapitiya=E2=80=99s office afterward to say that they wanted in on the de=
al. =E2=80=9CPeople either love Chamath or they hate him, and that=E2=80=99=
s fantastic, because polarization gets attention,=E2=80=9D the attendee sai=
d. =E2=80=9CPolarization gets you on CNBC, it gets you Twitter followers, i=
t gets you a megaphone. If you believe that Chamath can get an hour on CNBC=
 to explain Virgin Galactic, then you want to buy into this deal, because a=
ttention is money.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">I have bleeped some swears there; one way to be polarizing is by sweari=
ng a lot. =E2=80=9CEverybody wants in on this deal=E2=80=9D is a good way t=
o sell a deal, but =E2=80=9Call the young cool forward-thinking people want=
 in on this deal and all the stuck-in-the-past losers don't=E2=80=9D is som=
